<paper id="1526222424"><title>Optimal Key Ranking Procedures in a Statistical Cryptanalysis</title><year>2003</year><authors><author org="Security and Cryptography Laboratory" id="2172142368">Pascal Junod</author><author org="Security and Cryptography Laboratory" id="22805272">Serge Vaudenay</author></authors><n_citation>53</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>1493062108</reference><reference>1500414598</reference><reference>1535662987</reference><reference>1537206908</reference><reference>1542500920</reference><reference>1564295073</reference><reference>1964723977</reference><reference>2024048960</reference><reference>2027588622</reference><reference>2099473571</reference><reference>2105451999</reference><reference>2114197583</reference><reference>2168550363</reference></references><venue id="2758283624" type="C">Fast Software Encryption</venue><doi>10.1007/978-3-540-39887-5_18</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.66639">Higher-order differential cryptanalysis</keyword><keyword weight="0.60763">Block cipher</keyword><keyword weight="0.51204">Ranking</keyword><keyword weight="0.64581">Piling-up lemma</keyword><keyword weight="0.51862">Euclidean distance</keyword><keyword weight="0.45664">Algorithm</keyword><keyword weight="0.54361">Cryptanalysis</keyword><keyword weight="0.67567">Linear cryptanalysis</keyword><keyword weight="0.53807">Statistical hypothesis testing</keyword><keyword weight="0.41947">Mathematics</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>Hypothesis tests have been used in the past as a tool in a cryptanalytic context. In this paper, we propose to use this paradigm and define a precise and sound statistical framework in order to optimally mix information on independent attacked subkey bits obtained from any kind of statistical cryptanalysis. In the context of linear cryptanalysis, we prove that the best mixing paradigm consists of sorting key candidates by decreasing weighted Euclidean norm of the bias vector.</abstract></paper>